  "prompt": "What is indirect recursion?",
  "response": "Indirect recursion, also known as mutual recursion, is a type of recursion where two or more functions call each other in a cyclic manner to solve a problem. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\nKey Characteristics:\n1. Multiple functions are involved\n2. Each function calls another function\n3. The recursive calls form a cycle\n4. There must be a base case to prevent infinite recursion\n\nExample in Python:\n```python\ndef is_even(n):\n    if n == 0:\n        return True\n    else:\n        return is_odd(n - 1)\n\ndef is_odd(n):\n    if n == 0:\n        return False\n    else:\n        return is_even(n - 1)\n\n# Example usage\nprint(is_even(6))  # True\nprint(is_odd(7))   # True\n```\n\nAnother Example:\n```python\ndef function_a(n):\n    if n == 0:\n        return 0\n    return function_b(n - 1) + 1\n\ndef function_b(n):\n    if n == 0:\n        return 1\n    return function_a(n - 1) + 1\n\n# Example usage\nprint(function_a(5))  # 5\nprint(function_b(5))  # 5\n```\n\nCharacteristics:\n- More complex than direct recursion\n- Can be harder to understand and trace\n- Requires careful design to avoid infinite recursion\n- Useful for solving certain types of problems\n\nConsiderations:\n- Always ensure there's a base case\n- Be mindful of performance and stack overflow\n- Sometimes can be replaced with iterative solutions\n\nCommon Use Cases:\n- Parsing complex structures\n- Defining mutually recursive data types\n- Solving problems with interdependent conditions",
